Next is Batch 5: 140-addons.

This one is small. Right now it only covers kdump, which is good. I would not add more addon files yet unless we have a real need.

templates/partials/140-addons/_meta.yml

title: Installer addons
order: 140
required: true
selection: one
default: kdump_enabled
description: Controls optional Anaconda installer addons, such as kernel crash dump support.
applies_to:
  os:
    - rhel7
    - rhel8
    - rhel9
    - rhel10
  profiles:
    - minimal
    - small_disk
    - developer_workstation
options:
  - id: kdump_enabled
    file: kdump-enabled.ks.j2
    title: Enable kdump
    description: Enables kernel crash dump support so the system can capture diagnostic data after a kernel crash.
    recommended: true
    risk: low
    warning: Kdump reserves some memory for crash capture. This is normally worth keeping enabled on managed systems.
    requires: []
    conflicts:
      - kdump_disabled
    tags:
      - default
      - diagnostics
      - supportability
  - id: kdump_disabled
    file: kdump-disabled.ks.j2
    title: Disable kdump
    description: Disables kernel crash dump support.
    recommended: false
    risk: medium
    warning: Disabling kdump can make kernel crash troubleshooting harder.
    requires: []
    conflicts:
      - kdump_enabled
    tags:
      - diagnostics
      - small-systems
notes: Kdump is useful for troubleshooting kernel crashes. Keep it enabled by default unless the target system has very limited memory or a documented reason to disable it.
tags:
  - required
  - addons
  - kdump
  - diagnostics

templates/partials/140-addons/kdump-enabled.ks.j2

# Enable kdump crash capture support
%addon com_redhat_kdump --enable --reserve-mb='auto'
%end

templates/partials/140-addons/kdump-disabled.ks.j2

# Disable kdump crash capture support
%addon com_redhat_kdump --disable
%end

